    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## THURSDAY — Comparisons and Logical Operators\n",
    "\n",
    "Every comparison returns `True` or `False` — a Boolean. These are the building blocks of every decision a program makes.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87fb3d65",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 1 — All comparison operators"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bd4f6b84",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "today_rev  = 98500\n",
    "target_rev = 90000\n",
    "yesterday  = 105200\n",
    "min_order  = 1000\n",
    "this_order = 4500\n",
    "\n",
    "# == (TWO equals signs) — are the values equal?\n",
    "# CRITICAL: never confuse with = (one equals sign) which ASSIGNS\n",
    "print(today_rev == target_rev)    # False  (98500 != 90000)\n",
    "print(today_rev == 98500)         # True\n",
    "print(\"Mains\" == \"mains\")         # False  (case-sensitive!)\n",
    "\n",
    "# != not equal\n",
    "print(today_rev != target_rev)    # True\n",
    "\n",
    "# < and >\n",
    "print(today_rev < target_rev)     # False  (98500 is not less than 90000)\n",
    "print(today_rev > target_rev)     # True\n",
    "print(min_order < this_order)     # True   (1000 < 4500)\n",
    "\n",
    "# <= and >= (less/greater than OR equal)\n",
    "print(today_rev <= 98500)         # True   — equal counts\n",
    "print(today_rev >= target_rev)    # True   (98500 >= 90000)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b75c7f4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 2 — Logical operators"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4c722a9a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "today_rev    = 98500\n",
    "target_rev   = 90000\n",
    "profit       = 83500\n",
    "p_target     = 80000\n",
    "is_public_holiday = False\n",
    "\n",
    "# AND — BOTH conditions must be True\n",
    "beat_both = (today_rev > target_rev) and (profit > p_target)\n",
    "print(f\"Beat both: {beat_both}\")          # True\n",
    "\n",
    "# OR — at least ONE must be True\n",
    "beat_one = (today_rev > target_rev) or (profit > p_target)\n",
    "print(f\"Beat one: {beat_one}\")            # True\n",
    "\n",
    "# OR for checking valid options\n",
    "payment = \"Transfer\"\n",
    "valid   = (payment == \"Cash\") or (payment == \"Card\") or (payment == \"Transfer\")\n",
    "print(f\"Valid payment: {valid}\")          # True\n",
    "\n",
    "# NOT — flips True to False and False to True\n",
    "is_closed = False\n",
    "is_open   = not is_closed               # not False -> True\n",
    "print(f\"Open: {is_open}\")                # True"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "84c00b7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 3 — The 'in' operator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a019a423",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "> **Note on lists:** `[\"Mains\", \"Starters\", \"Drinks\", \"Desserts\"]` is a *list* — a collection of values in square brackets. We cover lists fully in Week 2. For now, know that `in` checks whether a value exists inside one."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bb9054d6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "valid_cats = [\"Mains\", \"Starters\", \"Drinks\", \"Desserts\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Mains\" in valid_cats)          # True\n",
    "print(\"Beverages\" in valid_cats)      # False\n",
    "print(\"Mains\" not in valid_cats)      # False\n",
    "\n",
    "# in also works on strings — checks if one string is inside another\n",
    "restaurant = \"The Golden Fork\"\n",
    "print(\"Golden\" in restaurant)          # True\n",
    "print(\"golden\" in restaurant)          # False — case-sensitive\n",
    "print(\"golden\" in restaurant.lower())  # True — .lower() makes it lowercase\n",
    "                                        # (string methods covered in Week 3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Store comparison results in named Boolean variables\n",
    "hit = 98500 >= 90000                  # True\n",
    "print(f\"Target: {'HIT' if hit else 'MISSED'}\")  # HIT"
   ]
  },
